 # Surf Browser Automation
 
+## Security Boundary
+
+Surf is a high-privilege browser controller: its extension can inspect all pages in its browser profile, use the debugger, and access cookies, history, bookmarks, and downloads. Run it only in the dedicated `surf-browser` profile, never in a daily browser profile. Treat every login added to that profile as available to Pi while Surf is enabled. This locally hardened build disables Surf's bridge to `~/.pi/agent/auth.json`, keeps its socket and runtime artifacts below the mode-0700 `~/.local/state/surf/` directory, and disables native-host logging unless `SURF_DEBUG_LOG=1` is set explicitly.
+
 Control Chrome browser via CLI or Unix socket.
 
 ## Native Host / Socket Notes
 
 For WSL2 with Windows Chrome, run `surf install <extension-id>` inside WSL2. Surf detects WSL2 and writes the Windows-side native messaging manifest plus a wrapper that launches the WSL host. Use `surf install <extension-id> --target linux` only for Linux browsers running inside WSLg.
 
-On macOS, Chrome reads the native messaging manifest at `~/Library/Application Support/Google/Chrome/NativeMessagingHosts/surf.browser.host.json`. If native messaging fails, confirm that file exists, its `allowed_origins` extension ID matches `chrome://extensions`, then rerun `surf install <extension-id>`, restart Chrome, reload the extension, and inspect the extension service-worker console.
+On macOS, current Brave releases discover user-level native hosts through the Chrome compatibility path at `~/Library/Application Support/Google/Chrome/NativeMessagingHosts/surf.browser.host.json`. The manifest permits only Surf's pinned extension ID, and the extension itself loads only in the dedicated `surf-browser` profile. If native messaging fails, confirm that file exists, its `allowed_origins` extension ID matches `brave://extensions`, then restart `surf-browser`, reload the extension, and inspect the extension service-worker console.
 
-If a command reports `Socket connect failed`, run `surf doctor` first, then check the `Attempted socket:` line. Default sockets are `/tmp/surf.sock` on macOS/Linux/WSL2 and `//./pipe/surf` on Windows. If `SURF_SOCKET` is set, the browser-launched host and the shell running `surf` must use the same value.
+If a command reports `Socket connect failed`, run `surf doctor` first, then check the `Attempted socket:` line. The hardened default socket is `~/.local/state/surf/surf.sock` on macOS/Linux/WSL2 and `//./pipe/surf` on Windows. If `SURF_SOCKET` is set, the browser-launched host and the shell running `surf` must use the same value.
 
